e no [[mortise and tenon]] fastenings, and no sewing. Shipwreck D may be one of the earliest [[lateen]]-rigged ships to be studied by archaeologists. The angle of the mast and the lack of fittings on it suggest that a lateen sail is the most likely configuration for such a small vessel. A 2007 expedition to the site, however, identified what may be a mast for an [[Headsail|artemon]], suggesting a different type of vessel.<ref>[http://www.archaeological.org/pdfs/2ndPeoples2008.pdf Deepwater investigations of two Byzantine shipwrecks, 2007]</ref>\n\nThe Institute for Exploration Black Sea expeditions relied on remote sensing with side-scan sonar in shallow and deep water to identify potential archaeological sites examined by [[Remotely operated underwater vehicle|ROV]]s. The hypothesis that the anoxic waters of the Black Sea would allow extraordinary organic preservation is borne out by the discovery of Sinop D, the 1,500-year-old shipwreck with excellent preservation of features above the sediment layer.<ref>Ballard, Robert D., and Ward, Cheryl, 2004, Deep-water Archaeological Survey in the Black Sea; 2000 Season, The International Journal of Nautical Archaeology, 33.1: 2-13.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the Black Sea Maritime Archaeology Project was initiated, which uncovered 41 shipwrecks off the Bulgarian coast of the Black Sea within just a few months of initiation. The ships were documented with 3D [[photogrammetry]], revealing their intricate details. Some of the ships were well preserved and date back to Byzantine times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2109843-dozens-of-ancient-shipwrecks-spotted-deep-beneath-the-black-sea/|title=Dozens of ancient shipwrecks spotted deep beneath the Black Sea|work=[[New Scientist]]|location=London|date=2016-10-20|accessdate=2017-09-16|first=Andy|last=Coghlan}}</ref> This technology also has potential for the study of shipwrecks from antiquity.\n\nIn 2018, a Roman trading vessel which dates back to 2nd\u20133rd centuries AD was found near [[Balaklava]], [[Crimean Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/ancient-roman-shipwreck-discovered-off-crimea-coast/|title=Ancient Roman shipwreck discovered off Crimea coast|work=UNTV News|date=10 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nAlso in 2018, a Greek merchant vessel dating to around 400 BC was discovered, almost completely intact, off the coast of the Bulgarian city of [[Burgas]] at a depth of roughly {{cvt|2000|m|mi|abbr=on}} by ROV. Thanks to the [[Anoxic waters|anoxic]] environment at this depth the ship was found on its side with it's hull, rudder, mast, and decking still all almost completely intact. The contents of the ship's hold was also found to be intact but could not be examined closely as the ships incredible preservation meant the hold remained largely sealed. At over 2,400 years old this wreck is considered the world's oldest intact shipwreck discovered to date.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ancient-origins.net/news-history-archaeology/ancient-shipwrecks-0010525|title=In the Depths for 2000 Years: Ancient Shipwrecks Discovered Back-to-Back in the Black Sea|work=Ancient Origins|date=11 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45951132|title='Oldest intact wreck' found in Black Sea|date=2018-10-23|access-date=2019-02-16|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ancient Black Sea Shipwrecks}}\n[[Category:Ancient Black Sea shipwrecks| ]]\n[[Category:Ancient Roman ships]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchaeology:Fixed doi error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Black_Sea_shipwrecks"}
{"title_page": "Marco Rose", "text_new": "{{short description|German footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Marco Rose\n| image = Fanclubs Weihnachtsfeier 64.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Rose in 2017\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|9|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Leipzig]], East Germany\n| height = 1.87 m\n| currentclub = [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] (coach)\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20131987\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rotation Leipzig]]\n| youthyears2 = 1987\u20132000\n| youthclubs2 = [[VfB Leipzig]]\n| years1 = 1995\u20132000\n| clubs1 = [[VfB Leipzig]]\n| caps1 = 57\n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs2 = [[Hannover 96]]\n| caps2 = 24\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2002\u20132010\n| clubs3 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05 II|Mainz 05 II]]\n| caps3 = 17\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2002\u20132010\n| clubs4 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]]\n| caps4 = 150\n| goals4 = 6\n| totalcaps = 248\n| totalgoals = 11\n| manageryears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| managerclubs1 = [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n| manageryears2 = 2013\u20132017\n| managerclubs2 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg (youth)|Red Bull Salzburg (youth)]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u20132019\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]]\n| manageryears4 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs4 = [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n}}\n'''Marco Rose''' (born 11 September 1976) is a German professional [[association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who currently manages [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]. As a player, he played as a defender for the likes of [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]], [[Hannover 96]] and [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]]. Later he coached Mainz 05 second team, then Lokomotive Leipzig, before going through the ranks at Red Bull Salzburg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2008-09/9053/vereinsspieler_marco-rose.html|title=Marco Rose|language=German|publisher=kicker.de|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/746100/artikel_offiziell_rose-wird-im-sommer-trainer-in-gladbach.html |title=Offiziell: Rose wird im Sommer Trainer in Gladbach |trans-title=Official: Rose becomes Gladbach manager in summer |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=10 April 2019 |access-date= 9 July 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n== Playing career ==\nThe defender started his career at Rotation Leipzig, and joined 1987 Lokomotive Leipzig, which later got renamed to VfB Leipzig. Rose played ten games in the second flight for VfB. In 2000, Rose joined Hannover 96. When Hannover reached promotion to the Bundesliga in 2002, Rose joined [[J\u00fcrgen Klopp]]'s Mainz on loan. When Mainz won itself the promotion to the Bundesliga, they signed Rose permanently. Rose resigned after 199 games for Mainz's first and second team. He scored seven goals, three of them in the Bundesliga.\n\n== Coaching career ==\n=== Early career ===\nRose started his career as assistant coach and player of Mainz's second team in the 2010\u201311 season. For the 2012\u201313 season, he joined Lokomotive Leipzig, but terminated his contract after one season.\n\n=== Salzburg ===\nRose joined RB Salzburg's U16 team in the 2013\u201314 season. When U18 coach Thomas Letsch joined FC Liefering, Rose succeeded him as U18 coach. The team won the Austrian U18 championship in his first season and the U19 Europa Youth League in April 2017 beating Benfica Lissabon 2\u20131 in the finals.\n\nFor the 2017\u201318 season, Rose succeeded Oscar Garcia as head coach of RB Salzburg.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/680121/artikel |title=Rose wird Coach bei RB Salzburg - Co-Trainer ist 24 |trans-title=Rose becomes RB Salzburg manager |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=15 June 2017 |access-date= 10 September 2019 |language=German}}</ref> In his first season, the team won the Austrian championship and reached the semi-finals of the Europa League, beating teams like Borussia Dortmund and Lazio. The final of the Austrian cup against Sturm Graz was lost. In the second season, RB Salzburg started the league with ten wins which broke the previous record of the league. In the Europa League they reached the quarter final against Napoli. Rose never lost a home game during his tenure as head coach of Salzburg.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://sport.orf.at/stories/3052851/ | title = Werner gl\u00e4nzt f\u00fcr Leipzig gegen Gladbach | trans-title = Werner shines for Leipzig against Gladbach | language = de | website = sport.orf.at | date = 30 August 2019 | access-date = 7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach ===\nFor the 2019\u201320 season, Rose joined Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/746100/artikel_offiziell_rose-wird-im-sommer-trainer-in-gladbach.html |title=Offiziell: Rose wird im Sommer Trainer in Gladbach |trans-title=Official: Rose becomes Gladbach manager in summer |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=10 April 2019 |access-date= 9 July 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRose is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://mobil.express.de/sport/fussball/borussia-moenchengladbach/-das-ist-mir-etwas-heiliges--rose-spricht-offen-ueber-weihnachten-und-seinen-glauben-33658516 | title = \u201eDas ist mir etwas Heiliges\u201c Rose spricht offen \u00fcber Weihnachten und seinen Glauben | trans-title = \"This is something holy for me\" Rose openly talks about Christmas and his faith | website =express.de | language = de | date = 24 December 2019 | access-date = 24 December 2019 | first = Achim | last = M\u00fcller}}</ref> His grandfather, [[Walter Rose (footballer)|Walter Rose]], was also a footballer who played for the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |title=Marco Rose: 5 things on Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach's inbound new head coach |website=[[Bundesliga]] |publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409205149/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 11 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title= Marco Rose career sheet|url=https://www.footballdatabase.eu/en/player/details/10032-marco-rose |work=footballdatabase |publisher=footballdatabase |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\t\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|align=left|1 July 2012\n|align=left|1 June 2013\n{{WDL|30|9|9|12|for=35|against=39|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/germany/1-fc-lokomotive-leipzig/11071/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]]\n|align=left|16 June 2017\n|align=left|30 June 2019\n{{WDL|114|81|23|10|for=269|against=88|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Red Bull Salzburg: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/austria/fc-red-bull-salzburg/165/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n|align=left|1 July 2019\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|33|18|6|9|for=57|against=41|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach: Matches |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/teams/germany/borussia-monchengladbach/971/|work=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|177|108|38|31|for=361|against=168|diff=yes}}\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n===Club===\n'''Hannover 96'''\n*[[2. Bundesliga]]: [[2001\u201302 2. Bundesliga|2001\u201302]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Red Bull Salzburg''' \n*[[Austrian Football Bundesliga|Austrian Bundesliga]]: [[2017\u201318 Austrian Football Bundesliga|2017\u201318]], [[2018\u201319 Austrian Football Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Austrian Cup]]: [[2018\u201319 Austrian Cup|2018\u201319]]\n\n'''Red Bull Salzburg \u2013 Youth'''\n*[[UEFA Youth League]]: [[2016\u201317 UEFA Youth League|2016\u201317]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}} {{in lang|de}}\n* {{Soccerway}}\n\n{{Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach squad}}\n{{Bundesliga managers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig managers}}\n{{FC Red Bull Salzburg managers}}\n{{Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rose, Marco}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German Christians]]\n[[Category:Converts to Christianity]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leipzig]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Saxony]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig players]]\n[[Category:Hannover 96 players]]\n[[Category:1. FSV Mainz 05 II players]]\n[[Category:1. FSV Mainz 05 players]]\n[[Category:2. Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:German football managers]]\n[[Category:1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig managers]]\n[[Category:FC Red Bull Salzburg managers]]\n[[Category:Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach managers]]\n[[Category:Austrian Football Bundesliga managers]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga managers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:German expatriate sportspeople in Austria]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Marco Rose\n| image = Fanclubs Weihnachtsfeier 64.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Rose in 2017\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|9|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Leipzig]], East Germany\n| height = 1.87 m\n| currentclub = [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] (coach)\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20131987\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rotation Leipzig]]\n| youthyears2 = 1987\u20132000\n| youthclubs2 = [[VfB Leipzig]]\n| years1 = 1995\u20132000\n| clubs1 = [[VfB Leipzig]]\n| caps1 = 57\n| goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 2000\u20132002\n| clubs2 = [[Hannover 96]]\n| caps2 = 24\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2002\u20132010\n| clubs3 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05 II|Mainz 05 II]]\n| caps3 = 17\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2002\u20132010\n| clubs4 = [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]]\n| caps4 = 150\n| goals4 = 6\n| totalcaps = 248\n| totalgoals = 11\n| manageryears1 = 2012\u20132013\n| managerclubs1 = [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n| manageryears2 = 2013\u20132017\n| managerclubs2 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg (youth)|Red Bull Salzburg (youth)]]\n| manageryears3 = 2017\u20132019\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]]\n| manageryears4 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs4 = [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]\n}}\n'''Marco Rose''' (born 11 September 1976) is a German professional [[association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who currently manages [[Bundesliga]] club [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]]. As a player, he played as a defender for the likes of [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]], [[Hannover 96]] and [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz]]. Later he coached Mainz 05 second team, then Lokomotive Leipzig, before going through the ranks at Red Bull Salzburg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/2008-09/9053/vereinsspieler_marco-rose.html|title=Marco Rose|language=German|publisher=kicker.de|accessdate=9 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/746100/artikel_offiziell_rose-wird-im-sommer-trainer-in-gladbach.html |title=Offiziell: Rose wird im Sommer Trainer in Gladbach |trans-title=Official: Rose becomes Gladbach manager in summer |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=10 April 2019 |access-date= 9 July 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n== Playing career ==\nThe defender started his career at Rotation Leipzig, and joined 1987 Lokomotive Leipzig, which later got renamed to VfB Leipzig. Rose played ten games in the second flight for VfB. In 2000, Rose joined Hannover 96. When Hannover reached promotion to the Bundesliga in 2002, Rose joined [[J\u00fcrgen Klopp]]'s Mainz on loan. When Mainz won itself the promotion to the Bundesliga, they signed Rose permanently. Rose resigned after 199 games for Mainz's first and second team. He scored seven goals, three of them in the Bundesliga.\n\n== Coaching career ==\n=== Early career ===\nRose started his career as assistant coach and player of Mainz's second team in the 2010\u201311 season. For the 2012\u201313 season, he joined Lokomotive Leipzig, but terminated his contract after one season.\n\n=== Salzburg ===\nRose joined RB Salzburg's U16 team in the 2013\u201314 season. When U18 coach Thomas Letsch joined FC Liefering, Rose succeeded him as U18 coach. The team won the Austrian U18 championship in his first season and the U19 Europa Youth League in April 2017 beating Benfica Lissabon 2\u20131 in the finals.\n\nFor the 2017\u201318 season, Rose succeeded Oscar Garcia as head coach of RB Salzburg.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/680121/artikel |title=Rose wird Coach bei RB Salzburg - Co-Trainer ist 24 |trans-title=Rose becomes RB Salzburg manager |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=15 June 2017 |access-date= 10 September 2019 |language=German}}</ref> In his first season, the team won the Austrian championship and reached the semi-finals of the Europa League, beating teams like Borussia Dortmund and Lazio. The final of the Austrian cup against Sturm Graz was lost. In the second season, RB Salzburg started the league with ten wins which broke the previous record of the league. In the Europa League they reached the quarter final against Napoli. Rose never lost a home game during his tenure as head coach of Salzburg.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://sport.orf.at/stories/3052851/ | title = Werner gl\u00e4nzt f\u00fcr Leipzig gegen Gladbach | trans-title = Werner shines for Leipzig against Gladbach | language = de | website = sport.orf.at | date = 30 August 2019 | access-date = 7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach ===\nFor the 2019\u201320 season, Rose joined Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/startseite/746100/artikel_offiziell_rose-wird-im-sommer-trainer-in-gladbach.html |title=Offiziell: Rose wird im Sommer Trainer in Gladbach |trans-title=Official: Rose becomes Gladbach manager in summer |website=kicker.de |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker]] |date=10 April 2019 |access-date= 9 July 2019 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRose is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://mobil.express.de/sport/fussball/borussia-moenchengladbach/-das-ist-mir-etwas-heiliges--rose-spricht-offen-ueber-weihnachten-und-seinen-glauben-33658516 | title = \u201eDas ist mir etwas Heiliges\u201c Rose spricht offen \u00fcber Weihnachten und seinen Glauben | trans-title = \"This is something holy for me\" Rose openly talks about Christmas and his faith | website =express.de | language = de | date = 24 December 2019 | access-date = 24 December 2019 | first = Achim | last = M\u00fcller}}</ref> His grandfather, [[Walter Rose]], was also a football who played for the [[Germany national football team|Germany national team]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |title=Marco Rose: 5 things on Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach's inbound new head coach |website=[[Bundesliga]] |publisher=[[Deutsche Fu\u00dfball Liga]] |date=11 April 2019 |access-date=9 April 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200409205149/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/marco-rose-5-things-on-borussia-monchengladbachs-inbound-new-head-coach-3651 |archive-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 11 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title= Marco Rose career sheet|url=https://www.footballdatabase.eu/en/player/details/10032-marco-rose |work=footballdatabase |publisher=footballdatabase |accessdate=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\t\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref|Reference}}\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig|Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|align=left|1 July 2012\n|align=left|1 June 2013\n{{WDL|30|9|9|